ume to provide an updated, panoramic view of public housing. With eleven chapters by prominent scholars, the collection not only covers a groundbreaking range of public housing issues transnationally but also does so in a revisionist and provocative manner. With students in mind, Public Housing Myths is organized thematically around popular preconceptions and myths about the policies surrounding big city public housing, the places themselves, and the people who call them home. The authors challenge narratives of inevitable decline, architectural determinism, and rampant criminality that have shaped earlier accounts and still dominate public perception.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCity planning. 0aPublic housingxEconomic aspects. 0aPublic housingxSocial aspects. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aHousing crisis, cost of living, housing policies, social issues, city housing, urban planning, urban development.1 aBloom, Nicholas Dagen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Nicholas Dagen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreemark, Yonah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerould, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeathcott, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, D. Bradford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwak, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevenstein, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmbach, Fritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUmbach, Fritz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUrban, Flor